Hi,

I agree with Zoltan that bionimial is probably inappropriate, for the reasons he stated.

I'm not sure that Tweedie is your solution though -- it is defined for non-negative real numbers.
 Not just those between 0 and 100%.  Perhaps easiest to think of fish biomass caught in a net (can be zero, or more.

Tweedie might work though, if your percentages are typically nowhere near the 100% boundary.  In this case, the upper end of the support is kind of immaterial...  You hope...

Does glmmTMB supply a beta distribution?  Zero-inflated beta?  The quantile regression idea might be useful too, as Brian suggested, but I'm not sure about random effects in that case.  Beta regression will also have problems with exactly 0% (or 100%) observations.

It seems, to me, that you might be forced to make a decision about what is 'least wrong', rather than what is 'best'.

Scott

